<br>
This is all true.  Most people aren't quickdraw artists who can beat a readied gun-wielder.  My example was unfair since the gun-wielder already has the upper-hand against anyone with or without a gun.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The case of a mugging is not really the best one to illustrate why gun-ownership advocates feel that it's important that people own guns.  It might seem far-fetched to you, Aurianne, but the whold &quot;defend myself against the government&quot; thing is really a primary motivation.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Everybody should go through self defense training, at the very least. Having acquired high level belts in Jiu Jitsu and Tae Kwon Do, I feel far more confident in my own abilities than I did before I started, and have learned a great deal about how to deal with situations where I'm accosted<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Why can't that self-defense training be with a gun?  Let's say that I spend 5 years learning how to shoot a gun and how to use a gun in situations where I'm accosted?  To go back to our earlier mugging example, you mentioned that you have techniques for disarming an attacker if you can get close enough.  If I've trained in defensive gun use for 5 years, it's likely that I've learned ways to draw and use my gun in sneaky ways that an attacker won't expect.  Let's assume that such defensive gun techniques exist.  Would you deny responsible citizens the right to choose that form of self-defense?  Or does everyone have to make the same self-defense choices that you make?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
If you feel overconfident because you have a gun in your hand, you are more likely to attempt to bring down your assailant, and if you're at the distance you propose, he's quite likely to see what you're doing and shoot first.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I assume that you don't feel overconfident in dangerous situations because you've trained yourself on how to handle them.  If I take 5 years of gun training, it's reasonable to assume that I will also avoid overconfidence in similar situations.<br>
<br>
If someone untrained in firearms use is overconfident in a dangerous situation and makes a mistake, it's exactly the same as someone who is untrained in hand-to-hand techniques making a similar mistake of overconfidence.  <br>
<br>
Even if a person *is* overconfident because they carry a gun without the proper training, any mistake they make will be their responsibility.  It goes back to this simple idea: just because someone is going to make an idiotic mistake doesn't mean that I will.  It is unfair to restrict me because of something someone else might do.  As I said in another thread, if someone use their car to kill someone they don't like, should you and I lose the right to drive?<br>
